					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7999552#post-4024141</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7999552/scp-6132-j#post-4024141</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sun, 14 Oct 2018 18:58:35 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Doctor Cimmerian</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1414765</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>I hold strongly to the view that jokes with a setup and a punchline should be as short as possible. Differing styles of -J's work differently (one that deals with a constant stream of absurdist humor could very well work better as it goes on and on for instance), but a feghoot's construction is very similar to the more basic setup-&gt;punchline.</p> <p>For me at least, a feghoot needs to be singularly focused on the pun at the end, otherwise you're wasting the reader's time. If people honestly think a carefully crafted joke is lazy because it's short, I can't do anything about that.</p> <p>Also, to be fair, the presentation is such that there's a little bit of additional absurdist humor in having all that security stuff at the start of an article about an SCP that you could put in a filing cabinet and have no issues with. It also works as a reference (along with the name, number, and a reference to Kirk Lonwood High School from the other class of '76 articles) to the original's format but still.</p> <p>Anyway, if I have to explain it, it wasn't funny to you in the first place. That's disappointing, but fair. I can't make everyone laugh.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7999552#post-4024131</guid>
